      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "International law, particularly the principle of *non-refoulement*, establishes a powerful moral and legal imperative that asylum seekers must be protected from being sent back to danger. Therefore, the humanitarian asylum argument is undeniably the stronger moral position when viewed through the lens of established universal human rights. A nation's right to control borders does not supersede the fundamental right to life and safety recognized globally.",
      "source": "target",
